WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.227 align:middle line:84%
[SQUEAKING]
[RUSTLING] [CLICKING]

00:00:06.227 --> 00:00:10.850 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:16.880 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So now
let's talk about, first,

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:22.980 align:middle line:84%
the different concepts that
we have talked about in class.

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:27.650 align:middle line:84%
And then in the end, I'll
get to just some example

00:00:27.650 --> 00:00:31.730 align:middle line:84%
of some problems that you
might face on the midterm.

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:37.490 align:middle line:84%
So the first is this, that
if you take a subset of R

00:00:37.490 --> 00:00:49.820 align:middle line:84%
in to say that A is
bounded from above,

00:00:49.820 --> 00:01:05.740 align:middle line:84%
it just means that there exists
M such that for all agent in A,

00:01:05.740 --> 00:01:07.840 align:middle line:84%
a here is less
than or equal to M.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:10.330 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it
means to be bounded

00:01:10.330 --> 00:01:12.160 align:middle line:90%
from above from a subset.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:15.890 align:middle line:90%
And now the least upper bound--

00:01:15.890 --> 00:01:18.640 align:middle line:90%


00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:22.600 align:middle line:90%
and this is a number.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:26.830 align:middle line:90%
So M here is at least--

00:01:26.830 --> 00:01:32.420 align:middle line:90%
so M is an upper bound.

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:39.610 align:middle line:90%


00:01:39.610 --> 00:01:58.330 align:middle line:84%
If M is an upper bound and
any other upper bound--

00:01:58.330 --> 00:02:03.860 align:middle line:90%


00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:05.610 align:middle line:90%
let's call it M bar--

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:08.300 align:middle line:90%


00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:15.290 align:middle line:84%
is equal to M. So
this is what it

00:02:15.290 --> 00:02:18.692 align:middle line:90%
means to be least upper bound.

00:02:18.692 --> 00:02:23.960 align:middle line:84%
And so the least
upper bound, this

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:28.104 align:middle line:84%
is what we denote
by sup of A. We'll

00:02:28.104 --> 00:02:36.080 align:middle line:84%
say that there is the
[INAUDIBLE] upper bound

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:52.590 align:middle line:84%
and similarly for
lower bound and inf.

00:02:52.590 --> 00:02:55.090 align:middle line:84%
And the real numbers
have this property

00:02:55.090 --> 00:03:00.730 align:middle line:84%
that if you set this
bounded from above, then

00:03:00.730 --> 00:03:06.610 align:middle line:84%
there is a least upper
bounds, and likewise for a set

00:03:06.610 --> 00:03:10.090 align:middle line:90%
that is probably from below.

00:03:10.090 --> 00:03:11.860 align:middle line:90%
OK, so that was sup.

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:16.000 align:middle line:84%
And we'll get to this
with lim sup and lim f.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.320 align:middle line:84%
I will just review that
a little bit later also.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:23.500 align:middle line:84%
But that's another
form of chain.

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:28.570 align:middle line:84%
A sequence-- so another key
concept in this part of class

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:30.610 align:middle line:90%
is sequence.

00:03:30.610 --> 00:03:33.780 align:middle line:84%
And we'll just begin with
a sequence of real numbers.

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:39.250 align:middle line:90%


00:03:39.250 --> 00:03:49.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is a map from the
positive integers into r.

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:51.370 align:middle line:90%
And again, we denote--

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:58.740 align:middle line:84%
so the image-- so if you're
looking at the image of some n,

00:03:58.740 --> 00:04:04.050 align:middle line:84%
we typically denote this by a
n or by a n or xn or something

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:08.850 align:middle line:84%
like that, where we
use this subscript.

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:11.490 align:middle line:84%
But it's just the
image under this map.

00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:13.750 align:middle line:90%
So that's a sequence.

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:21.269 align:middle line:84%
So for each positive integer,
you get a real number.

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:28.410 align:middle line:84%
Then for a sequence,
one of the first things

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:31.120 align:middle line:84%
you were interested
in is convergence.

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:36.730 align:middle line:90%


00:04:36.730 --> 00:04:45.720 align:middle line:84%
So if this here is a sequence,
that xn converges to some x

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:56.930 align:middle line:84%
here, this just means that for
all epsilon greater than 0,

00:04:56.930 --> 00:04:58.000 align:middle line:90%
there exist--

00:04:58.000 --> 00:04:59.450 align:middle line:90%
I will use this symbol.

00:04:59.450 --> 00:05:03.310 align:middle line:84%
I haven't used it until now, but
it's just so hard not to use it.

00:05:03.310 --> 00:05:06.070 align:middle line:90%
This here means there exists--

00:05:06.070 --> 00:05:09.460 align:middle line:90%
it's not on the midterm.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:11.750 align:middle line:84%
But it's a pretty
standard symbol.

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:20.290 align:middle line:84%
So there exists a capital
N such that if little n is

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:28.450 align:middle line:84%
equal to capital N, then xn
minus x is smaller than epsilon.

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:33.820 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it means for
a sequence to converge to x.

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:35.710 align:middle line:84%
Sequence xn is equal
or greater to x.

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:37.130 align:middle line:90%
And we write it like this.

00:05:37.130 --> 00:05:40.240 align:middle line:84%
Or you can write xn
and then the limit

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:44.170 align:middle line:84%
here as n goes to
infinity is equal to x.

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:49.830 align:middle line:90%
Both of these are standard use.

00:05:49.830 --> 00:06:08.280 align:middle line:84%
And then also, if a sequence
is not converged, then

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:13.667 align:middle line:90%
we say it is divergent.

00:06:13.667 --> 00:06:16.410 align:middle line:90%


00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:21.900 align:middle line:84%
So the sequence is either
convergent or it's divergent.

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:39.330 align:middle line:84%
And then you have this property,
useful property, so a lemma

00:06:39.330 --> 00:06:50.770 align:middle line:84%
If xn is convergent,
then the set--

00:06:50.770 --> 00:06:52.460 align:middle line:90%
this here as a set--

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:55.130 align:middle line:90%
this here is a bounded set.

00:06:55.130 --> 00:07:00.520 align:middle line:90%


00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:03.340 align:middle line:90%
So we'll talk about that.

00:07:03.340 --> 00:07:06.760 align:middle line:84%
And then another
thing about sequences

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:19.730 align:middle line:84%
is that the algebraic
properties of sequences--

00:07:19.730 --> 00:07:23.410 align:middle line:90%


00:07:23.410 --> 00:07:26.020 align:middle line:84%
and what are the
algebraic properties?

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:29.800 align:middle line:84%
They are that if you take
two sequences a n, b n--

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:37.570 align:middle line:84%
and let's say that a n converge
to a and b n and converts to b.

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:40.245 align:middle line:90%
And c let's is just a constant.

00:07:40.245 --> 00:07:44.690 align:middle line:90%


00:07:44.690 --> 00:07:47.250 align:middle line:84%
And often, when
you combine what I

00:07:47.250 --> 00:07:49.590 align:middle line:90%
did, those one and two before--

00:07:49.590 --> 00:07:50.310 align:middle line:90%
you combine.

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:53.650 align:middle line:84%
You're looking at a
and plus c times b.

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:57.780 align:middle line:84%
And this here converge
to a plus c times b.

00:07:57.780 --> 00:07:58.960 align:middle line:90%
This is the first.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:01.230 align:middle line:84%
And when I state it
like this, it actually

00:08:01.230 --> 00:08:03.300 align:middle line:84%
combine two of
the one properties

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:06.330 align:middle line:90%
that we talked about earlier.

00:08:06.330 --> 00:08:14.430 align:middle line:84%
The second one is that a n times
bn will converge to n times b.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:22.410 align:middle line:84%
Third property is that if a n,
if this here are not equal to 0

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:25.590 align:middle line:84%
and the limit here
is not equal to 0,

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:28.650 align:middle line:90%
then 1 over a n converge to 1/a.

00:08:28.650 --> 00:08:31.530 align:middle line:90%


00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:34.890 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course,
this last one,

00:08:34.890 --> 00:08:37.679 align:middle line:84%
this one implies
in particular that

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:42.950 align:middle line:90%
also bn over an inverse b/a.

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:45.590 align:middle line:84%
This is just because
this property here

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:48.080 align:middle line:90%
combined with the property 2.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:51.680 align:middle line:90%
That would give you this.

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:52.474 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:52.474 --> 00:08:57.530 align:middle line:84%
So that's the algebraic
properties of limits.

00:08:57.530 --> 00:09:06.060 align:middle line:84%
And then you have the concept of
a subsequence, so a subsequence.

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:11.720 align:middle line:90%


00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:15.950 align:middle line:84%
So we imagine that
we have a sequence.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.680 align:middle line:84%
And often, we don't go all
the way back like this.

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:24.620 align:middle line:84%
But a sequence, again, is a
map from the positive integer

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:32.750 align:middle line:84%
into R. And we denote the
image of n typically like xn.

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:36.110 align:middle line:84%
Then a subsequence of
this sequence-- and this

00:09:36.110 --> 00:09:38.870 align:middle line:84%
is typically denoted
something like this, where

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:41.250 align:middle line:90%
you have a further subscript.

00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:45.420 align:middle line:84%
And this is important,
again, that this

00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:51.360 align:middle line:90%
is like equal to f of g of k.

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:55.500 align:middle line:84%
Whereas g here-- and this is
a really important property--

00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:59.820 align:middle line:84%
that g is a map from
the positive integers

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:01.810 align:middle line:90%
into the positive integers.

00:10:01.810 --> 00:10:05.220 align:middle line:84%
And then really
important is that g here

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:07.420 align:middle line:90%
is strictly increasing.

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:14.280 align:middle line:90%


00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:17.250 align:middle line:84%
And so strictly
increasing guarantee you

00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:22.860 align:middle line:84%
that these numbers here is
taken in the same order as

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:24.690 align:middle line:90%
in the original sequence.

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:27.570 align:middle line:90%
But you may skip a bunch.

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:29.700 align:middle line:84%
You take one, and then
you may skip a bunch.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:31.170 align:middle line:90%
And then you take another one.

00:10:31.170 --> 00:10:32.620 align:middle line:90%
And then you may skip more.

00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:35.160 align:middle line:90%
But it's in the same order.

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:40.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's what strictly
increasing is guaranteeing.

00:10:40.070 --> 00:10:47.580 align:middle line:84%
And then you have
this property that's--

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:58.490 align:middle line:84%
so you have this theorem that
a sequence xn is convergent if

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:15.290 align:middle line:84%
and only if all
subsequences are convergent

00:11:15.290 --> 00:11:20.330 align:middle line:84%
And one of the two directions
for this here was trivial.

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:24.900 align:middle line:90%


00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:28.950 align:middle line:84%
Because if you take a
sequence, then it is--

00:11:28.950 --> 00:11:31.310 align:middle line:84%
if you're thinking
about this map here, g,

00:11:31.310 --> 00:11:34.470 align:middle line:90%
as being the identity--

00:11:34.470 --> 00:11:36.030 align:middle line:84%
so that would give
you a subsequence.

00:11:36.030 --> 00:11:38.650 align:middle line:84%
But that really is
the original sequence.

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:42.580 align:middle line:84%
So the original sequence
is a subsequence of itself.

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:45.940 align:middle line:84%
So if all subsequence are
convergent, well then,

00:11:45.940 --> 00:11:48.620 align:middle line:84%
in particular, the sequence
itself is convergent.

00:11:48.620 --> 00:11:52.540 align:middle line:84%
So one of those two
iterations was trivial.

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:54.001 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:54.001 --> 00:12:00.080 align:middle line:84%
Now then we had
these two theorems.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:07.130 align:middle line:84%
So the thing in mathematics is
that things build on each other.

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:11.090 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully-- each
step is fairly trivial,

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:13.220 align:middle line:90%
but you build step by step.

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:16.660 align:middle line:84%
And then you end up with
something highly nontrivial.

00:12:16.660 --> 00:12:20.470 align:middle line:90%
So this here was pretty trivial.

00:12:20.470 --> 00:12:25.850 align:middle line:84%
But then we used it later on
to prove something nontrivial.

00:12:25.850 --> 00:12:28.340 align:middle line:84%
So this was this monotone
convergence theorem.

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:36.920 align:middle line:90%


00:12:36.920 --> 00:12:41.000 align:middle line:84%
And there was two
versions of this.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.840 align:middle line:90%
You had a sequence xn.

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:50.720 align:middle line:90%
And xn was increasing.

00:12:50.720 --> 00:12:52.760 align:middle line:84%
So that means that
the next element

00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:55.340 align:middle line:84%
is bigger or equal to
the previous element.

00:12:55.340 --> 00:12:58.520 align:middle line:84%
If this here was
the case, then xn

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:13.850 align:middle line:84%
is convergent if and
only if xn is bounded,

00:13:13.850 --> 00:13:16.910 align:middle line:90%
if the sequence is bounded.

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:26.310 align:middle line:84%
And the sup of the xn, this
here, this is the limit.

00:13:26.310 --> 00:13:28.970 align:middle line:90%


00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.960 align:middle line:90%
This here is the limit.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:41.290 align:middle line:90%


00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:44.950 align:middle line:84%
And the second
version of this is,

00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:48.470 align:middle line:84%
if you have a monotone-- so
instead of being increasing,

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:49.700 align:middle line:90%
it's now decreasing.

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:52.940 align:middle line:84%
So the next element
is smaller or

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:55.480 align:middle line:90%
equal to the previous element.

00:13:55.480 --> 00:14:07.390 align:middle line:84%
And then similarly, the sequence
xn is convergent if and only

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:15.590 align:middle line:90%
if xn is bounded from below.

00:14:15.590 --> 00:14:23.260 align:middle line:90%


00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:27.020 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, and if
it is bounded from below,

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:33.340 align:middle line:84%
then the limit
here of xn is inf.

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:36.090 align:middle line:90%


00:14:36.090 --> 00:14:36.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:36.590 --> 00:14:39.230 align:middle line:84%
So that was the
monotone convergence.

00:14:39.230 --> 00:14:42.890 align:middle line:84%
And it has these two versions,
the increasing version

00:14:42.890 --> 00:14:46.280 align:middle line:90%
and the decreasing version.

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:55.280 align:middle line:84%
Then another important concept
was that of a Cauchy sequence.

00:14:55.280 --> 00:15:00.920 align:middle line:84%
And the reason why
Cauchy sequence

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:05.330 align:middle line:84%
is useful, even for
the real numbers--

00:15:05.330 --> 00:15:08.150 align:middle line:84%
later on, we generalize
these concepts.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:12.300 align:middle line:84%
It was obvious demonstration
of the concept of convergence,

00:15:12.300 --> 00:15:16.430 align:middle line:84%
but also of there being a Cauchy
sequence to metric spaces.

00:15:16.430 --> 00:15:20.750 align:middle line:84%
But even for the real
numbers, Cauchy sequence,

00:15:20.750 --> 00:15:24.530 align:middle line:84%
you might be interested
in whether a sequence is

00:15:24.530 --> 00:15:25.620 align:middle line:90%
convergent.

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:29.290 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes, it's
much easier to prove

00:15:29.290 --> 00:15:32.410 align:middle line:84%
that it's a Cauchy sequence
than to prove that it actually

00:15:32.410 --> 00:15:33.430 align:middle line:90%
is convergent.

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:37.280 align:middle line:84%
And so if you don't really
care about what the limit is,

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:42.585 align:middle line:84%
then it's often easier to prove
that it's a Cauchy sequence.

00:15:42.585 --> 00:15:46.960 align:middle line:90%


00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:51.950 align:middle line:84%
So Cauchy sequence, so you
have a sequence-- again,

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:55.840 align:middle line:90%
we're still in the real numbers.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:58.600 align:middle line:90%
And this is a Cauchy sequence.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:00.730 align:middle line:90%
It just means that for all--

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:04.120 align:middle line:84%
and now I will use
also this here.

00:16:04.120 --> 00:16:06.440 align:middle line:84%
This symbol just
means "for all."

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:08.240 align:middle line:84%
And that's also a
standard symbol.

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:10.840 align:middle line:90%
It's an inverted A.

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:15.490 align:middle line:84%
For all epsilon greater
than 0, there exist--

00:16:15.490 --> 00:16:21.070 align:middle line:84%
again, this here,
inverted E, means

00:16:21.070 --> 00:16:34.890 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital N such
that if little n and little m

00:16:34.890 --> 00:16:39.480 align:middle line:84%
are bigger than capital N,
then those two elements are

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:43.620 align:middle line:90%
bunched epsilon close together.

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:47.820 align:middle line:84%
[INAUDIBLE] This
is what it means.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:51.630 align:middle line:84%
For a sequence to
be Cauchy sequence,

00:16:51.630 --> 00:16:55.670 align:middle line:84%
then the tail of the sequence
lies very, very close together.

00:16:55.670 --> 00:16:58.650 align:middle line:90%


00:16:58.650 --> 00:17:06.720 align:middle line:90%
Then let me skip--

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:09.060 align:middle line:84%
in my notes, I have
something about contracting.

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:11.602 align:middle line:84%
But actually, there won't be
anything about contracting that.

00:17:11.602 --> 00:17:12.910 align:middle line:90%
So I'll skip that.

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:20.069 align:middle line:90%


00:17:20.069 --> 00:17:24.569 align:middle line:84%
Let me next talk about
the Cauchy convergence

00:17:24.569 --> 00:17:29.115 align:middle line:84%
theorem and the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:17:29.115 --> 00:17:39.940 align:middle line:90%


00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:52.960 align:middle line:84%
So Cauchy-- also, let me
just remind you that, again,

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:53.960 align:middle line:90%
on the midterm--

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:56.440 align:middle line:84%
so there are these
five main problems.

00:17:56.440 --> 00:17:58.780 align:middle line:84%
Then there's the
six bonus problems.

00:17:58.780 --> 00:18:03.120 align:middle line:90%
But make sure that you--

00:18:03.120 --> 00:18:05.300 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter
which one you do.

00:18:05.300 --> 00:18:08.920 align:middle line:84%
So you might as well
start with the ones

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:14.620 align:middle line:90%
that seems easiest to you.

00:18:14.620 --> 00:18:18.040 align:middle line:84%
And you can see here where it
says exactly how many points

00:18:18.040 --> 00:18:19.040 align:middle line:90%
each of them give.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:24.430 align:middle line:84%
So if you don't have enough
time to finish all of it,

00:18:24.430 --> 00:18:26.396 align:middle line:84%
you can make sure
to try to optimize.

00:18:26.396 --> 00:18:28.790 align:middle line:90%


00:18:28.790 --> 00:18:29.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:29.290 --> 00:18:31.210 align:middle line:84%
So what is the Cauchy
convergence theorem?

00:18:31.210 --> 00:18:38.710 align:middle line:84%
So again, we are in
R. And we have n.

00:18:38.710 --> 00:18:42.120 align:middle line:84%
So the Cauchy convergence
theorem [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:42.120 --> 00:18:58.348 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that if xn is a Cauchy
sequence, then xn is convergent.

00:18:58.348 --> 00:19:02.100 align:middle line:90%


00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:05.070 align:middle line:90%
That's a Cauchy convergence.

00:19:05.070 --> 00:19:07.130 align:middle line:84%
Then for Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem--

00:19:07.130 --> 00:19:12.510 align:middle line:90%


00:19:12.510 --> 00:19:17.190 align:middle line:84%
and this Cauchy convergence
theorem, we talked about that.

00:19:17.190 --> 00:19:23.940 align:middle line:84%
So the concepts, when we in a
minute review metric spaces,

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:27.995 align:middle line:84%
then convergence sequence, that
makes sense in the metric space.

00:19:27.995 --> 00:19:31.105 align:middle line:84%
Cauchy sequence makes
sense in the metric space.

00:19:31.105 --> 00:19:34.170 align:middle line:90%


00:19:34.170 --> 00:19:38.970 align:middle line:84%
And the statement of the theorem
makes sense in a metric space.

00:19:38.970 --> 00:19:41.600 align:middle line:84%
But it's not always
that it holds.

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:46.280 align:middle line:84%
It holds in R, but it doesn't
hold in a general metric space.

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:53.300 align:middle line:84%
The Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem statement of that

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:55.830 align:middle line:84%
also makes sense in a
general metric space,

00:19:55.830 --> 00:19:59.360 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't hold in
a general metric space.

00:19:59.360 --> 00:20:04.705 align:middle line:84%
So again, these are things
about the real numbers.

00:20:04.705 --> 00:20:07.220 align:middle line:90%


00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:09.720 align:middle line:84%
They extend to more
than a real number.

00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:16.600 align:middle line:84%
But for other spaces, you
have to prove it individually.

00:20:16.600 --> 00:20:18.830 align:middle line:84%
So Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem says

00:20:18.830 --> 00:20:28.800 align:middle line:84%
that if xn is a
bounded sequence,

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:35.680 align:middle line:84%
then xn has a
convergent subsequence.

00:20:35.680 --> 00:20:43.000 align:middle line:90%


00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:43.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:43.500 --> 00:20:45.250 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:47.670 align:middle line:90%


00:20:47.670 --> 00:20:52.110 align:middle line:84%
And the next thing
I want to review

00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:55.690 align:middle line:84%
is what it means for a
function to be continuous.

00:20:55.690 --> 00:20:58.870 align:middle line:84%
So continuity is another
important property.

00:20:58.870 --> 00:21:03.360 align:middle line:84%
It's closely tied together
with this whole sequence.

00:21:03.360 --> 00:21:05.015 align:middle line:84%
And we'll get to that
in just a minute.

00:21:05.015 --> 00:21:21.920 align:middle line:90%


00:21:21.920 --> 00:21:27.230 align:middle line:90%
So if you have a function--

00:21:27.230 --> 00:21:31.310 align:middle line:84%
let's say on R, but it could
be defined on a subset of R--

00:21:31.310 --> 00:21:33.410 align:middle line:84%
so if you have a
function like this,

00:21:33.410 --> 00:21:46.990 align:middle line:84%
then we say that f here is
continuous at x0 if for all--

00:21:46.990 --> 00:21:50.870 align:middle line:90%


00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:58.310 align:middle line:84%
it's continuous at x0 if for
all epsilon greater than 0,

00:21:58.310 --> 00:22:07.490 align:middle line:84%
there exists a delta
greater than 0 such that

00:22:07.490 --> 00:22:14.130 align:middle line:84%
f x minus x0 is
smaller than delta.

00:22:14.130 --> 00:22:27.010 align:middle line:84%
Then the image is
smaller than epsilon

00:22:27.010 --> 00:22:30.380 align:middle line:84%
So that's what it means for
a function to be continuous.

00:22:30.380 --> 00:22:38.750 align:middle line:84%
And there was this theorem or
lemma that tied things together.

00:22:38.750 --> 00:23:01.420 align:middle line:84%
So lemma-- if f is continuous
at x0 and xn converges to x0,

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:09.530 align:middle line:84%
then the images
of the sequence--

00:23:09.530 --> 00:23:11.470 align:middle line:90%
so that's another sequence--

00:23:11.470 --> 00:23:15.320 align:middle line:90%
converges to f of x0.

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:18.480 align:middle line:84%
So we proved this even
in a metric space.

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:21.585 align:middle line:90%
But normally those two are not.

00:23:21.585 --> 00:23:22.085 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:22.085 --> 00:23:26.030 align:middle line:90%


00:23:26.030 --> 00:23:31.320 align:middle line:84%
And then we had the algebraic
properties of functions.

00:23:31.320 --> 00:23:34.280 align:middle line:84%
And they were very
similar to this.

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:38.210 align:middle line:84%
So let me just review them,
so algebraic properties

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:39.265 align:middle line:90%
of continuous function.

00:23:39.265 --> 00:23:59.930 align:middle line:90%


00:23:59.930 --> 00:24:11.950 align:middle line:84%
So continuous functions-- so
imagine that you have f and g

00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:13.730 align:middle line:90%
are continuous functions.

00:24:13.730 --> 00:24:18.490 align:middle line:90%


00:24:18.490 --> 00:24:26.080 align:middle line:84%
So everything is defined
on R. c here is a constant.

00:24:26.080 --> 00:24:30.970 align:middle line:84%
Well, then property one that
corresponds to that property one

00:24:30.970 --> 00:24:35.810 align:middle line:84%
is that this function plus
c times this function here,

00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:38.090 align:middle line:90%
this here is also continuous.

00:24:38.090 --> 00:24:44.230 align:middle line:90%


00:24:44.230 --> 00:24:49.210 align:middle line:84%
And then two is that
if this function here

00:24:49.210 --> 00:24:56.710 align:middle line:84%
is never equal to 0, then
1 over this function here,

00:24:56.710 --> 00:24:58.370 align:middle line:90%
this is also continuous.

00:24:58.370 --> 00:25:01.270 align:middle line:90%


00:25:01.270 --> 00:25:03.500 align:middle line:90%
And sorry, that was not true.

00:25:03.500 --> 00:25:04.000 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:05.540 align:middle line:84%
I shouldn't have
made that mistake.

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:07.510 align:middle line:84%
I should make that the
third property, sorry--

00:25:07.510 --> 00:25:12.470 align:middle line:84%
that f times g is
also continuous.

00:25:12.470 --> 00:25:16.760 align:middle line:84%
And then the third property
would be that if f is not equal

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:19.160 align:middle line:84%
to 0-- that would
correspond to that--

00:25:19.160 --> 00:25:23.930 align:middle line:84%
then this function here
is also continuous.

00:25:23.930 --> 00:25:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And again, I divided
it up when I did it.

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:30.890 align:middle line:84%
I divided it up into four
steps to separate this out

00:25:30.890 --> 00:25:34.230 align:middle line:90%
into two steps OK.

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:37.380 align:middle line:84%
And so from this
one, we got that--

00:25:37.380 --> 00:25:40.220 align:middle line:84%
just because then we proved
that the constant function

00:25:40.220 --> 00:25:41.640 align:middle line:90%
was continuous.

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:45.410 align:middle line:84%
And the linear function, the
function f of x equal to x

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:46.710 align:middle line:90%
is continuous.

00:25:46.710 --> 00:25:51.770 align:middle line:84%
Once we have that, then
we just use one and two

00:25:51.770 --> 00:25:58.050 align:middle line:84%
to prove that all
polynomials is continuous.

00:25:58.050 --> 00:26:00.680 align:middle line:84%
And then if we bring
in three, then we

00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:05.060 align:middle line:84%
have this with all rational
functions are continuous except,

00:26:05.060 --> 00:26:10.220 align:middle line:84%
of course, where the
denominator vanishes.

00:26:10.220 --> 00:26:10.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:15.040 align:middle line:84%
So that was how you build
continuous functions

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:19.120 align:middle line:90%
from noncontinuous functions.

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:24.460 align:middle line:84%
And then we proved the extreme
value and the intermediate value

00:26:24.460 --> 00:26:25.030 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:26.500 align:middle line:90%
We had these two theorem.

00:26:26.500 --> 00:26:27.740 align:middle line:90%
And they were proved--

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:30.820 align:middle line:84%
so one way to prove it
that we did last time

00:26:30.820 --> 00:26:37.510 align:middle line:84%
was to use this lemma
that tie together

00:26:37.510 --> 00:26:40.300 align:middle line:90%
continuity and sequences.

00:26:40.300 --> 00:26:44.950 align:middle line:84%
And so we had the
extreme value theorem.

00:26:44.950 --> 00:26:48.520 align:middle line:84%
And this just say that if you
have a function-- but now it's

00:26:48.520 --> 00:26:53.530 align:middle line:84%
crucial that this here
is a bounded interval

00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:56.960 align:middle line:84%
and the endpoints
are included in this.

00:26:56.960 --> 00:26:59.200 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
function like this,

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:06.360 align:middle line:84%
and this function is
continuous, then the sup

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:12.100 align:middle line:84%
and the inf over the set here
is achieved or, if you will,

00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:19.880 align:middle line:84%
the max of f and
min of f achieved.

00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:24.630 align:middle line:90%


00:27:24.630 --> 00:27:28.530 align:middle line:84%
In particular, the
function is bounded.

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:31.830 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just state it like
this with a brief, like that.

00:27:31.830 --> 00:27:34.300 align:middle line:84%
So that was the
extreme value theorem.

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:38.040 align:middle line:84%
The intermediate value
theorem is saying

00:27:38.040 --> 00:27:40.350 align:middle line:90%
that if you have a function--

00:27:40.350 --> 00:27:44.040 align:middle line:84%
imagine that starting off
here and ending there.

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:46.170 align:middle line:90%
So this is the function.

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:48.240 align:middle line:84%
The intermediate
value theorem say

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:51.150 align:middle line:84%
that everything in
between these two

00:27:51.150 --> 00:27:53.700 align:middle line:90%
is also the image of something.

00:27:53.700 --> 00:28:01.950 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that f of a
is smaller than f of b.

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:08.770 align:middle line:84%
And y here is between
f and a and f of b.

00:28:08.770 --> 00:28:18.160 align:middle line:84%
Then there exist x between a and
b so that f of x is equal to 1.

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:22.130 align:middle line:84%
Again, the functions we're
talking about are continuous,

00:28:22.130 --> 00:28:28.355 align:middle line:84%
and they are defined
on this interval.

00:28:28.355 --> 00:28:28.855 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:28.855 --> 00:28:30.480 align:middle line:90%
So that was those two theorems.

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:33.070 align:middle line:90%


00:28:33.070 --> 00:28:40.570 align:middle line:84%
And they used some
property about that--

00:28:40.570 --> 00:28:42.370 align:middle line:90%
they used two things.

00:28:42.370 --> 00:28:45.040 align:middle line:84%
They used the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:50.830 align:middle line:84%
And then they used how sequences
are continuous functions,

00:28:50.830 --> 00:28:52.090 align:middle line:90%
both tied together.

00:28:52.090 --> 00:28:55.810 align:middle line:84%
The Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem is using something

00:28:55.810 --> 00:28:58.540 align:middle line:84%
about that the real
numbers are ordered

00:28:58.540 --> 00:29:02.220 align:middle line:90%
and like this with sup and inf.

00:29:02.220 --> 00:29:05.640 align:middle line:84%
You have the least upper bound
property and the greatest lower

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:06.345 align:middle line:90%
bound property.

00:29:06.345 --> 00:29:08.970 align:middle line:90%


00:29:08.970 --> 00:29:09.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:13.290 align:middle line:84%
And another thing--
so we talked about--

00:29:13.290 --> 00:29:17.580 align:middle line:84%
so some of the highlights,
in terms of concepts,

00:29:17.580 --> 00:29:22.710 align:middle line:84%
are sequences and
continuity of functions

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:26.320 align:middle line:84%
and then various properties
that follow from this.

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:30.660 align:middle line:90%
Then another thing is series.

00:29:30.660 --> 00:29:34.865 align:middle line:90%
So that's another key concept.

00:29:34.865 --> 00:29:39.750 align:middle line:90%


00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:49.760 align:middle line:84%
So series-- so series is when
you're starting with a sequence.

00:29:49.760 --> 00:29:55.500 align:middle line:90%


00:29:55.500 --> 00:30:01.490 align:middle line:84%
So series-- so you're
starting with-- so this here

00:30:01.490 --> 00:30:02.860 align:middle line:90%
is a sequence.

00:30:02.860 --> 00:30:06.200 align:middle line:90%


00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:12.410 align:middle line:84%
And now you form
another sequence, Sn.

00:30:12.410 --> 00:30:13.880 align:middle line:90%
But here, you're summing.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:17.400 align:middle line:84%
And it could start wherever
you want to start it.

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:19.760 align:middle line:90%
Let's say it start from 0.

00:30:19.760 --> 00:30:21.390 align:middle line:90%
You're summing the first--

00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:24.050 align:middle line:84%
in this case, it would be,
because you're starting at 0,

00:30:24.050 --> 00:30:27.080 align:middle line:84%
you're summing the
first n plus 1.

00:30:27.080 --> 00:30:33.200 align:middle line:84%
So ai-- and this
here is a0 plus a n.

00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:36.480 align:middle line:84%
We just write n
plus 1 in this case.

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:38.270 align:middle line:90%
You don't have to start at 0.

00:30:38.270 --> 00:30:41.930 align:middle line:84%
You start at 1, it would
be the first n numbers.

00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:45.770 align:middle line:84%
So you're looking at--
so a series is really

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:47.010 align:middle line:90%
kind of the same thing.

00:30:47.010 --> 00:30:48.420 align:middle line:84%
But you think about it
a little bit different.

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:50.060 align:middle line:84%
But it's really the same
thing as a sequence.

00:30:50.060 --> 00:30:51.560 align:middle line:84%
But you're starting
with a sequence,

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:54.050 align:middle line:84%
and then you form
a new sequence.

00:30:54.050 --> 00:30:58.760 align:middle line:84%
And then the key question
here is-- the key question--

00:30:58.760 --> 00:31:06.120 align:middle line:90%


00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:12.528 align:middle line:90%
is the series convergent or not?

00:31:12.528 --> 00:31:21.060 align:middle line:90%


00:31:21.060 --> 00:31:23.040 align:middle line:90%
So that's a key question.

00:31:23.040 --> 00:31:27.030 align:middle line:84%
And if it is convergent--
and the series

00:31:27.030 --> 00:31:31.050 align:middle line:90%
is often written like this.

00:31:31.050 --> 00:31:36.390 align:middle line:84%
And so this here will
symbolize the series.

00:31:36.390 --> 00:31:39.090 align:middle line:84%
And if the series
is convergent, it

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:40.870 align:middle line:90%
will also symbolize the limit.

00:31:40.870 --> 00:31:42.620 align:middle line:90%
So it has two meanings.

00:31:42.620 --> 00:31:46.240 align:middle line:90%


00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:48.850 align:middle line:84%
But even if it's not
convergent, then--

00:31:48.850 --> 00:31:51.510 align:middle line:84%
well, if it's not convergent,
you would just write down

00:31:51.510 --> 00:31:55.910 align:middle line:84%
and you would think
about this S series.

00:31:55.910 --> 00:32:04.190 align:middle line:84%
Now there are some series
that are particular important.

00:32:04.190 --> 00:32:09.200 align:middle line:84%
And they can then be used
to determine whether or not

00:32:09.200 --> 00:32:13.130 align:middle line:90%
other series are convergent.

00:32:13.130 --> 00:32:14.550 align:middle line:90%
So let me just review them.

00:32:14.550 --> 00:32:18.370 align:middle line:84%
And the most important of
all is the geometric series.

00:32:18.370 --> 00:32:25.580 align:middle line:90%


00:32:25.580 --> 00:32:33.430 align:middle line:84%
And the geometric series
is the series c to the n,

00:32:33.430 --> 00:32:36.800 align:middle line:90%
n equals to 0 to infinity.

00:32:36.800 --> 00:32:41.640 align:middle line:84%
And c is just some fixed
number, real number.

00:32:41.640 --> 00:32:44.690 align:middle line:90%
And you're looking at this.

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:48.890 align:middle line:84%
And this was the
geometric series.

00:32:48.890 --> 00:33:00.550 align:middle line:84%
And this is convergent if
the absolute value of c

00:33:00.550 --> 00:33:04.236 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1 and
divergent otherwise.

00:33:04.236 --> 00:33:12.850 align:middle line:90%


00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:19.060 align:middle line:84%
And if it is convergent
when c and absolute value

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:30.040 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1, then this sum
here is equal to 1 times c.

00:33:30.040 --> 00:33:32.390 align:middle line:90%
But remember two things.

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:35.630 align:middle line:84%
One is that when you actually
want to evaluate the sum,

00:33:35.630 --> 00:33:37.730 align:middle line:90%
it's crucial where you start.

00:33:37.730 --> 00:33:41.960 align:middle line:84%
If I started at 1, then it's
not any more equal to this.

00:33:41.960 --> 00:33:46.030 align:middle line:84%
But you have to subtract the
first element that was missing.

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:50.240 align:middle line:84%
So for convergence, it doesn't
matter where you start.

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:54.170 align:middle line:90%
But for the limits, it's key.

00:33:54.170 --> 00:33:55.260 align:middle line:90%
That's one thing.

00:33:55.260 --> 00:33:59.780 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing is
that when you-- again, we

00:33:59.780 --> 00:34:03.680 align:middle line:84%
talk about this, that when
you're given a series, even

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:06.930 align:middle line:84%
before there's any question,
when you have a series,

00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:10.610 align:middle line:84%
the first thing you look at
is, does this a n converge to 0

00:34:10.610 --> 00:34:12.129 align:middle line:90%
or not?

00:34:12.129 --> 00:34:16.850 align:middle line:84%
If a n does not go to 0, the
series is not going to converge.

00:34:16.850 --> 00:34:21.956 align:middle line:84%
There's no need to
apply any fancy test.

00:34:21.956 --> 00:34:26.040 align:middle line:84%
And for a series, the
question is always

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:27.489 align:middle line:90%
whether it's convergent or not.

00:34:27.489 --> 00:34:32.617 align:middle line:90%


00:34:32.617 --> 00:34:37.370 align:middle line:90%
So that's a geometric series.

00:34:37.370 --> 00:34:41.929 align:middle line:84%
And then there are two other
series that we talked about.

00:34:41.929 --> 00:34:42.949 align:middle line:90%
And let me just--

00:34:42.949 --> 00:34:45.889 align:middle line:90%


00:34:45.889 --> 00:34:49.600 align:middle line:84%
not only talk about, but we
also determined whether or not

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:52.210 align:middle line:90%
they were convergent.

00:34:52.210 --> 00:34:55.420 align:middle line:84%
Then we used them to determine
whether other series were

00:34:55.420 --> 00:34:58.840 align:middle line:90%
convergent.

00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:01.750 align:middle line:84%
But again, the most
important of all of them

00:35:01.750 --> 00:35:03.190 align:middle line:90%
is the geometric series.

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:06.640 align:middle line:84%
That's the one that
we use to determine

00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:10.610 align:middle line:84%
whether power series in
general are converging or not.

00:35:10.610 --> 00:35:13.540 align:middle line:84%
But there are two others
that are worth mentioning.

00:35:13.540 --> 00:35:15.060 align:middle line:90%
One is the harmonic series.

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:20.350 align:middle line:90%


00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:26.320 align:middle line:84%
The harmonic series is the
series where you're summing 1/n.

00:35:26.320 --> 00:35:30.660 align:middle line:90%
So this here is divergent.

00:35:30.660 --> 00:35:34.480 align:middle line:90%
So this follows second.

00:35:34.480 --> 00:35:39.070 align:middle line:84%
And then there's a
closely related--

00:35:39.070 --> 00:35:41.740 align:middle line:90%
let's call it 2 and 1/2--

00:35:41.740 --> 00:35:44.300 align:middle line:84%
that's called the
alternating harmonic series.

00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:53.750 align:middle line:90%


00:35:53.750 --> 00:35:57.950 align:middle line:84%
So the alternating, it was
like the harmonic series,

00:35:57.950 --> 00:36:00.838 align:middle line:84%
but the sine of it
was alternating.

00:36:00.838 --> 00:36:03.710 align:middle line:90%


00:36:03.710 --> 00:36:06.000 align:middle line:84%
And this here is
actually convergent.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:10.310 align:middle line:90%


00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:15.990 align:middle line:84%
So there's 1, 2, 2 and
1/2, and then there's 3.

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:22.460 align:middle line:90%
And that's this series here.

00:36:22.460 --> 00:36:24.380 align:middle line:90%
We look at this series here.

00:36:24.380 --> 00:36:26.558 align:middle line:90%
And this here was convergent.

00:36:26.558 --> 00:36:30.470 align:middle line:90%


00:36:30.470 --> 00:36:33.755 align:middle line:84%
The only one where we
determine what the sum was

00:36:33.755 --> 00:36:35.545 align:middle line:84%
was actually the
geometric series.

00:36:35.545 --> 00:36:39.795 align:middle line:90%


00:36:39.795 --> 00:36:40.295 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:40.295 --> 00:36:43.150 align:middle line:90%
So that's some key series.

00:36:43.150 --> 00:36:56.710 align:middle line:90%


00:36:56.710 --> 00:36:59.830 align:middle line:84%
Then when you have
a series, there

00:36:59.830 --> 00:37:03.850 align:middle line:84%
was one concept that we
proved to be quite useful.

00:37:03.850 --> 00:37:12.790 align:middle line:84%
And that was the concept of
absolute convergent of a series.

00:37:12.790 --> 00:37:15.340 align:middle line:90%


00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:18.940 align:middle line:84%
And so you're
looking at a series.

00:37:18.940 --> 00:37:26.170 align:middle line:84%
And absolute convergence
was that this sum here

00:37:26.170 --> 00:37:28.330 align:middle line:90%
was convergent.

00:37:28.330 --> 00:37:37.480 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
absolutely convergent

00:37:37.480 --> 00:37:42.790 align:middle line:84%
if this series, where the n
replaced by the absolute value

00:37:42.790 --> 00:37:43.640 align:middle line:90%
was convergence.

00:37:43.640 --> 00:37:44.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:50.070 align:middle line:84%
So of course, for a series
of non-negative numbers,

00:37:50.070 --> 00:37:51.990 align:middle line:84%
if it's convergent,
it's automatically

00:37:51.990 --> 00:37:54.060 align:middle line:90%
absolutely convergent.

00:37:54.060 --> 00:37:57.600 align:middle line:84%
And we talked about
it a little bit,

00:37:57.600 --> 00:38:02.100 align:middle line:84%
that one of the things
about absolute convergence

00:38:02.100 --> 00:38:04.740 align:middle line:84%
is that you could
kind of reorder

00:38:04.740 --> 00:38:06.690 align:middle line:84%
the way you're
summing things, and it

00:38:06.690 --> 00:38:08.460 align:middle line:90%
wouldn't matter for the limit.

00:38:08.460 --> 00:38:12.557 align:middle line:84%
But if it's not absolute
convergent, that really matters.

00:38:12.557 --> 00:38:13.390 align:middle line:90%
We thought about it.

00:38:13.390 --> 00:38:15.070 align:middle line:84%
We didn't really
prove anything there.

00:38:15.070 --> 00:38:18.630 align:middle line:84%
But I think it was kind of
clear, you could do this.

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:21.060 align:middle line:84%
One thing where we
used it was that when

00:38:21.060 --> 00:38:25.590 align:middle line:84%
we look at products of series,
then the product of series

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:29.290 align:middle line:84%
was convergent if each of
them was absolute convergent.

00:38:29.290 --> 00:38:33.180 align:middle line:84%
And there, you saw that we
estimated some remainder term.

00:38:33.180 --> 00:38:35.070 align:middle line:84%
And there, it was
really kind of key

00:38:35.070 --> 00:38:39.160 align:middle line:84%
that we had absolute
convergence.

00:38:39.160 --> 00:38:42.190 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so absolute
convergence is an important--

00:38:42.190 --> 00:38:45.640 align:middle line:90%


00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:48.650 align:middle line:84%
it's a stronger property
than convergence.

00:38:48.650 --> 00:38:52.100 align:middle line:84%
So absolute convergence
implies convergence.

00:38:52.100 --> 00:38:54.190 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I should write this there.

00:38:54.190 --> 00:38:57.131 align:middle line:84%
So we had the theorem,
so absolute convergence.

00:38:57.131 --> 00:39:03.730 align:middle line:90%


00:39:03.730 --> 00:39:06.850 align:middle line:84%
So this implies
convergence, but it's

00:39:06.850 --> 00:39:08.265 align:middle line:90%
stronger, generally stronger.

00:39:08.265 --> 00:39:11.390 align:middle line:90%


00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:11.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:11.890 --> 00:39:17.500 align:middle line:90%
And then we had some tests.

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:18.770 align:middle line:90%
Then we had some tests.

00:39:18.770 --> 00:39:23.470 align:middle line:84%
And so we talked in
particular about--

00:39:23.470 --> 00:39:27.700 align:middle line:84%
there was a few other
tests that we talked about.

00:39:27.700 --> 00:39:33.400 align:middle line:84%
But they're not actually
going to be on the midterm.

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:36.970 align:middle line:84%
And some of them,
we'll get back to.

00:39:36.970 --> 00:39:38.880 align:middle line:84%
This one here won't
be on the midterm.

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:40.470 align:middle line:90%
You'll have the alternating.

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:45.510 align:middle line:84%
But we talked about how
to prove the convergence.

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:47.970 align:middle line:84%
And when we talk
about it, then we

00:39:47.970 --> 00:39:51.720 align:middle line:84%
discovered that this thing
here, that it was a stronger

00:39:51.720 --> 00:39:54.360 align:middle line:84%
statement that if
you have alternating

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:57.450 align:middle line:84%
and the a n were
all non-negative

00:39:57.450 --> 00:40:03.900 align:middle line:84%
and these guys was decreasing,
decreasing down to 0, then

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:07.770 align:middle line:84%
actually, any alternating
sequence like that

00:40:07.770 --> 00:40:11.490 align:middle line:90%
would be convergent.

00:40:11.490 --> 00:40:14.580 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, but for
the test, we really

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:17.170 align:middle line:90%
talk about was three tests.

00:40:17.170 --> 00:40:18.620 align:middle line:90%
One of them had two parts.

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:22.950 align:middle line:90%


00:40:22.950 --> 00:40:27.570 align:middle line:84%
And then in a minute, we'll
talk about how we apply them

00:40:27.570 --> 00:40:31.680 align:middle line:90%
to power series [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:40.610 align:middle line:84%
So we had some
tests to determine

00:40:40.610 --> 00:40:46.345 align:middle line:90%
whether or not a series--

00:40:46.345 --> 00:40:56.650 align:middle line:90%


00:40:56.650 --> 00:40:57.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:58.290 align:middle line:90%
So what are the tests?

00:40:58.290 --> 00:41:00.415 align:middle line:84%
So there are the
comparison tests.

00:41:00.415 --> 00:41:03.860 align:middle line:90%


00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:06.680 align:middle line:84%
Let me just first
write down the test.

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:09.110 align:middle line:84%
So the comparison test--
and there was two versions,

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:12.470 align:middle line:90%
version a and version b.

00:41:12.470 --> 00:41:14.950 align:middle line:90%
Then there was the ratio test.

00:41:14.950 --> 00:41:19.610 align:middle line:90%


00:41:19.610 --> 00:41:22.051 align:middle line:84%
And then there
was the root test.

00:41:22.051 --> 00:41:28.790 align:middle line:90%


00:41:28.790 --> 00:41:30.990 align:middle line:84%
The ratio test
and the root test,

00:41:30.990 --> 00:41:36.510 align:middle line:84%
they are both offsprings
of the geometric series.

00:41:36.510 --> 00:41:39.100 align:middle line:90%
And both of these, you got--

00:41:39.100 --> 00:41:41.790 align:middle line:84%
let's just talk
about this first.

00:41:41.790 --> 00:41:48.270 align:middle line:84%
The ratio test was looking
at this, the ratio of a n,

00:41:48.270 --> 00:41:54.180 align:middle line:84%
[INAUDIBLE] divided by a
n, a n plus 1 over a n.

00:41:54.180 --> 00:41:58.980 align:middle line:84%
So you are implicitly assuming
that the a n does not vanish.

00:41:58.980 --> 00:42:00.150 align:middle line:90%
I'm not sure.

00:42:00.150 --> 00:42:03.060 align:middle line:90%
So you can form this ratio.

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:08.820 align:middle line:84%
And then as n goes to
infinity, if this limit here

00:42:08.820 --> 00:42:15.960 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1,
then the ratio tests

00:42:15.960 --> 00:42:20.640 align:middle line:84%
say that the series
was convergent.

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:26.010 align:middle line:84%
If the ratio was bigger than 1,
then this ordinary element, a n,

00:42:26.010 --> 00:42:27.475 align:middle line:90%
would not even go to 0.

00:42:27.475 --> 00:42:30.490 align:middle line:90%


00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:32.310 align:middle line:90%
So in this case here--

00:42:32.310 --> 00:42:33.810 align:middle line:90%
maybe I'll write it over here.

00:42:33.810 --> 00:42:48.770 align:middle line:90%


00:42:48.770 --> 00:42:52.235 align:middle line:84%
So the ratio test, you
assume that the a is not

00:42:52.235 --> 00:42:54.830 align:middle line:90%
if the a n equals 0.

00:42:54.830 --> 00:43:00.620 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking at
a n plus 1 over a n.

00:43:00.620 --> 00:43:02.720 align:middle line:90%
And if this limit here--

00:43:02.720 --> 00:43:06.140 align:middle line:90%


00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:08.070 align:middle line:84%
let's assume that
the limit exists.

00:43:08.070 --> 00:43:10.280 align:middle line:84%
Of course, it may
not exist, right?

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:13.310 align:middle line:90%
But if the limit existed--

00:43:13.310 --> 00:43:19.200 align:middle line:90%
so if c here is less than 1--

00:43:19.200 --> 00:43:22.160 align:middle line:84%
it's always non-negative because
these are non-negative numbers.

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:26.227 align:middle line:84%
If c is less than 1, then
the series is convergent.

00:43:26.227 --> 00:43:30.800 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.800 --> 00:43:34.500 align:middle line:84%
If this c here is
strictly bigger than 1,

00:43:34.500 --> 00:43:41.610 align:middle line:84%
we should find that the
series is divergent.

00:43:41.610 --> 00:43:45.065 align:middle line:84%
And if the c was equal
to 1, then it's unclear--

00:43:45.065 --> 00:43:48.840 align:middle line:90%


00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:55.230 align:middle line:84%
and so unclear, which means
that further tests are needed.

00:43:55.230 --> 00:44:02.260 align:middle line:90%
And so that's the ratio test.

00:44:02.260 --> 00:44:04.175 align:middle line:90%
And the root test are similar.

00:44:04.175 --> 00:44:06.810 align:middle line:90%


00:44:06.810 --> 00:44:08.170 align:middle line:90%
The root tests were--

00:44:08.170 --> 00:44:10.890 align:middle line:90%
so you're looking at the a n.

00:44:10.890 --> 00:44:13.650 align:middle line:84%
You take the-- so
this is the root test.

00:44:13.650 --> 00:44:17.790 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is
tested by comparing these

00:44:17.790 --> 00:44:19.740 align:middle line:90%
to the geometric series.

00:44:19.740 --> 00:44:22.350 align:middle line:90%
So the root test--

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:29.330 align:middle line:90%
so you the n-th root of this.

00:44:29.330 --> 00:44:31.700 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking
at the limit here.

00:44:31.700 --> 00:44:36.290 align:middle line:84%
And we actually
looked at the lim sup.

00:44:36.290 --> 00:44:38.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm writing the lim sup.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:42.140 align:middle line:84%
The reason why I
want the lim sup is

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:46.160 align:middle line:90%
that I want to make sure--

00:44:46.160 --> 00:44:49.110 align:middle line:84%
later on, I want to
apply more generally.

00:44:49.110 --> 00:44:51.980 align:middle line:90%


00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:58.790 align:middle line:84%
So if the lim sup
here was less than 1--

00:44:58.790 --> 00:45:00.980 align:middle line:90%
lim sup is called a c.

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:07.230 align:middle line:84%
If c here is less than 1,
then the series is convergent.

00:45:07.230 --> 00:45:12.260 align:middle line:90%


00:45:12.260 --> 00:45:16.960 align:middle line:84%
Two, if the c is bigger
than 1, series is divergent.

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:21.620 align:middle line:84%
This fails the most
basic test, divergent.

00:45:21.620 --> 00:45:26.520 align:middle line:84%
And again, three, if c is
equal to 1, then it's unclear,

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:28.230 align:middle line:90%
failed test [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:28.230 --> 00:45:31.630 align:middle line:90%


00:45:31.630 --> 00:45:34.930 align:middle line:90%
That was those two tests.

00:45:34.930 --> 00:45:38.330 align:middle line:84%
The comparison tests,
let's get back to that.

00:45:38.330 --> 00:45:40.585 align:middle line:84%
The comparison
test had two parts.

00:45:40.585 --> 00:45:43.600 align:middle line:90%


00:45:43.600 --> 00:45:46.900 align:middle line:90%
Suppose you had a n and bn.

00:45:46.900 --> 00:45:49.150 align:middle line:84%
The first part is
this statement,

00:45:49.150 --> 00:45:52.300 align:middle line:84%
that if you have two
series, one based

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:55.420 align:middle line:84%
on the a n, another
series based on the bn,

00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:59.200 align:middle line:90%
if you have this, if bn--

00:45:59.200 --> 00:46:07.270 align:middle line:84%
so this here, if this
series here is convergent,

00:46:07.270 --> 00:46:11.291 align:middle line:84%
then it implies
this is convergent.

00:46:11.291 --> 00:46:14.590 align:middle line:90%


00:46:14.590 --> 00:46:19.820 align:middle line:84%
And this is sometimes used
both exactly like this,

00:46:19.820 --> 00:46:21.730 align:middle line:84%
and it's also
sometimes used where

00:46:21.730 --> 00:46:23.930 align:middle line:84%
you know that this
one here is divergent.

00:46:23.930 --> 00:46:27.950 align:middle line:84%
And so you compute
this one [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:30.830 align:middle line:84%
The other part of
the comparison test

00:46:30.830 --> 00:46:37.430 align:middle line:84%
was if you had the limit here,
if this limit here exists and it

00:46:37.430 --> 00:46:41.060 align:middle line:90%
was some f.

00:46:41.060 --> 00:46:43.740 align:middle line:90%
then actually, it said that--

00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:47.690 align:middle line:84%
let's say L here
is not equal to 0.

00:46:47.690 --> 00:46:56.700 align:middle line:84%
Then if one of
them is convergent,

00:46:56.700 --> 00:46:58.110 align:middle line:84%
the other one is
also convergent.

00:46:58.110 --> 00:47:01.230 align:middle line:90%
So if a n--

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:06.920 align:middle line:84%
or bn, let's say--
bn is convergent,

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:14.130 align:middle line:84%
it implies that a n is
convergent and vice versa.

00:47:14.130 --> 00:47:17.400 align:middle line:84%
This actually prove that
this here is convergent,

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:18.540 align:middle line:90%
if you [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:18.540 --> 00:47:21.050 align:middle line:90%
It's convergent.

00:47:21.050 --> 00:47:23.140 align:middle line:84%
So those were the
three tests artists

00:47:23.140 --> 00:47:24.740 align:middle line:90%
that we really went through.

00:47:24.740 --> 00:47:26.870 align:middle line:84%
There was a few other
tests, like, again,

00:47:26.870 --> 00:47:30.020 align:middle line:84%
this alternating series
test that you saw the proof,

00:47:30.020 --> 00:47:31.780 align:middle line:84%
but it's not going
to be on midterms.

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:33.800 align:middle line:84%
And we will return
to this later.

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:34.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:47:34.720 --> 00:47:37.060 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Are there
[? patterns ?] of when

00:47:37.060 --> 00:47:38.735 align:middle line:90%
we should apply which tests?

00:47:38.735 --> 00:47:39.610 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:47:39.610 --> 00:47:40.280 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:46.260 align:middle line:84%
And I want to get to
this in just a second.

00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:49.900 align:middle line:90%


00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:52.780 align:middle line:84%
Let me just say a
couple of words first.

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:56.150 align:middle line:84%
Let me jump to some of
the examples of problems.

00:47:56.150 --> 00:48:00.061 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll come back and
I'll review a little bit more.

00:48:00.061 --> 00:48:02.660 align:middle line:84%
But let's just talk
about power series--

00:48:02.660 --> 00:48:05.170 align:middle line:90%


00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:10.240 align:middle line:84%
and maybe a little
interesting whether--

00:48:10.240 --> 00:48:14.215 align:middle line:84%
just now, when you were
asking the question--

00:48:14.215 --> 00:48:14.890 align:middle line:90%
no.

00:48:14.890 --> 00:48:17.311 align:middle line:84%
Let's just review
the power series.

00:48:17.311 --> 00:48:21.000 align:middle line:90%


00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:24.480 align:middle line:84%
So our power series
was a series,

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:27.120 align:middle line:84%
but it was something that
also defined a function.

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:33.660 align:middle line:90%


00:48:33.660 --> 00:48:40.760 align:middle line:90%
So you have a power change.

00:48:40.760 --> 00:48:46.170 align:middle line:90%


00:48:46.170 --> 00:48:49.080 align:middle line:90%
So you have a sequence a n.

00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:51.990 align:middle line:84%
And then you're
saying for each x--

00:48:51.990 --> 00:48:53.970 align:middle line:90%
sigma x is being fixed.

00:48:53.970 --> 00:48:56.910 align:middle line:90%
You form a series.

00:48:56.910 --> 00:49:00.100 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
series that you form.

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:03.180 align:middle line:90%


00:49:03.180 --> 00:49:06.150 align:middle line:84%
And so for each
x, you can ask, is

00:49:06.150 --> 00:49:08.370 align:middle line:90%
this series convergent or not?

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:12.000 align:middle line:84%
This here is called
a power series.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:18.940 align:middle line:84%
And the key point for power
series is, again, of course,

00:49:18.940 --> 00:49:21.460 align:middle line:84%
whether or not
this is convergent.

00:49:21.460 --> 00:49:25.250 align:middle line:84%
And this gave rise to the
radius of convergence.

00:49:25.250 --> 00:49:31.540 align:middle line:90%


00:49:31.540 --> 00:49:37.700 align:middle line:84%
And so the radius of convergence
was that we defined--

00:49:37.700 --> 00:49:50.570 align:middle line:84%
we looked at lim sup of the
n-th root of a n, like that.

00:49:50.570 --> 00:49:58.360 align:middle line:84%
And we looked at if
this thing here actually

00:49:58.360 --> 00:50:02.410 align:middle line:90%
defined this thing here.

00:50:02.410 --> 00:50:05.110 align:middle line:90%
And so we get this thing here.

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:07.700 align:middle line:84%
And then we define the
radius of convergence.

00:50:07.700 --> 00:50:16.390 align:middle line:84%
So the radius of
convergence, this is r.

00:50:16.390 --> 00:50:20.618 align:middle line:84%
And r is 1 over
this [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:20.618 --> 00:50:23.370 align:middle line:90%


00:50:23.370 --> 00:50:27.540 align:middle line:84%
But there was an
understanding in this.

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:33.180 align:middle line:84%
The understanding is that
this number here, this number

00:50:33.180 --> 00:50:36.840 align:middle line:90%
potentially could be infinite.

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:40.140 align:middle line:84%
If it was infinite, it
meant that this thing here

00:50:40.140 --> 00:50:46.560 align:middle line:84%
was 0, if this one
here is this infinity.

00:50:46.560 --> 00:50:53.958 align:middle line:84%
If this here is 0, then
this here would be infinity.

00:50:53.958 --> 00:50:57.630 align:middle line:84%
So that's like a convention
in this particular case.

00:50:57.630 --> 00:51:00.670 align:middle line:84%
Usually, we don't want to
divide by 0 [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:05.280 align:middle line:84%
But this is a convention
in this particular case.

00:51:05.280 --> 00:51:08.220 align:middle line:84%
And so using this
radius of convergence,

00:51:08.220 --> 00:51:11.050 align:middle line:84%
we saw that if you
take a power series,

00:51:11.050 --> 00:51:15.380 align:middle line:84%
if you have any power series
like this, then you have

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:16.790 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE].

00:51:16.790 --> 00:51:20.180 align:middle line:84%
Any power cells like
this, it's going

00:51:20.180 --> 00:51:25.580 align:middle line:84%
to be-- if this is R
And again, R could be 0,

00:51:25.580 --> 00:51:27.980 align:middle line:90%
or it could be infinity.

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:30.290 align:middle line:90%
But if this is R--

00:51:30.290 --> 00:51:33.050 align:middle line:84%
sorry, I should write
this minus sign.

00:51:33.050 --> 00:51:40.220 align:middle line:84%
Then for x in between, for x
not including the endpoints but

00:51:40.220 --> 00:51:43.920 align:middle line:84%
in between, the
series is convergent.

00:51:43.920 --> 00:51:45.590 align:middle line:90%
The power series is convergent.

00:51:45.590 --> 00:51:49.680 align:middle line:84%
And outside here,
this is divergent.

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:52.730 align:middle line:90%


00:51:52.730 --> 00:51:54.270 align:middle line:90%
Outside is divergent.

00:51:54.270 --> 00:51:55.635 align:middle line:90%
Here is convergent.

00:51:55.635 --> 00:51:58.430 align:middle line:90%


00:51:58.430 --> 00:52:01.760 align:middle line:84%
And at those two
points here, unclear.

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:04.550 align:middle line:90%


00:52:04.550 --> 00:52:06.720 align:middle line:90%
Other tests are needed.

00:52:06.720 --> 00:52:08.630 align:middle line:90%
So this is always this picture.

00:52:08.630 --> 00:52:13.350 align:middle line:84%
So this comes back to your
question about which test--

00:52:13.350 --> 00:52:17.310 align:middle line:84%
of course, you can
use any test you want.

00:52:17.310 --> 00:52:18.990 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking
at a series, you

00:52:18.990 --> 00:52:20.770 align:middle line:90%
can use whatever test you want.

00:52:20.770 --> 00:52:23.760 align:middle line:84%
But if it was a power
series, you already

00:52:23.760 --> 00:52:31.150 align:middle line:84%
know that there's some interval
around 0 where it's convergent.

00:52:31.150 --> 00:52:35.930 align:middle line:84%
And then there's a question
about the endpoints.

00:52:35.930 --> 00:52:36.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:36.430 --> 00:52:41.495 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look at
some examples of this.

00:52:41.495 --> 00:52:44.100 align:middle line:90%


00:52:44.100 --> 00:52:47.470 align:middle line:90%
And suppose you look at--

00:52:47.470 --> 00:52:58.080 align:middle line:84%
and so it's usually not too
hard to use either the root--

00:52:58.080 --> 00:53:05.070 align:middle line:84%
to use either-- this here
was based on the root test.

00:53:05.070 --> 00:53:08.790 align:middle line:84%
So you're using the root test or
the ratio test for power series.

00:53:08.790 --> 00:53:11.700 align:middle line:84%
But you can take
advantage of it.

00:53:11.700 --> 00:53:14.070 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes it's just
slightly easier.

00:53:14.070 --> 00:53:16.250 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at
two examples here.

00:53:16.250 --> 00:53:32.360 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that you ask to
find the radius of convergence

00:53:32.360 --> 00:53:33.450 align:middle line:90%
for the power series.

00:53:33.450 --> 00:53:39.690 align:middle line:90%


00:53:39.690 --> 00:53:40.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:40.190 --> 00:53:45.830 align:middle line:84%
And then let's say that this
is n to the fifth power xn.

00:53:45.830 --> 00:53:50.750 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that this is the
power series you're given.

00:53:50.750 --> 00:53:55.410 align:middle line:84%
And you want to find the
radius of convergence.

00:53:55.410 --> 00:54:03.450 align:middle line:84%
You can either just
plug it into this test.

00:54:03.450 --> 00:54:06.690 align:middle line:84%
Or you can just say,
OK, we'll just apply it.

00:54:06.690 --> 00:54:08.460 align:middle line:90%
We know that it's some interval.

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:10.770 align:middle line:84%
And I just want to
see, for which x,

00:54:10.770 --> 00:54:12.510 align:middle line:90%
does this here converge?

00:54:12.510 --> 00:54:14.700 align:middle line:84%
So if I looked,
in this case, you

00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:20.070 align:middle line:84%
might find it slightly
easier to do the root test.

00:54:20.070 --> 00:54:23.980 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at the n
plus 1 element in this series--

00:54:23.980 --> 00:54:26.430 align:middle line:90%
the n element, sorry.

00:54:26.430 --> 00:54:29.840 align:middle line:84%
The n element would be
this to the fifth power.

00:54:29.840 --> 00:54:32.140 align:middle line:90%
Think about x as being fixed.

00:54:32.140 --> 00:54:34.410 align:middle line:90%
And you're asking, for which x?

00:54:34.410 --> 00:54:39.780 align:middle line:84%
And then for a given x, you want
to determine whether this series

00:54:39.780 --> 00:54:44.220 align:middle line:90%
here is convergent.

00:54:44.220 --> 00:54:46.920 align:middle line:84%
So if you're using
the root test,

00:54:46.920 --> 00:54:48.690 align:middle line:84%
you would look at
this thing here.

00:54:48.690 --> 00:54:51.060 align:middle line:84%
And you might find, in
this case, slightly easier

00:54:51.060 --> 00:54:53.580 align:middle line:90%
to use the root test.

00:54:53.580 --> 00:54:56.280 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking
at this, this thing

00:54:56.280 --> 00:55:02.760 align:middle line:84%
here is now n plus 1 to the
fifth power times x to the n

00:55:02.760 --> 00:55:10.040 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 divided by n to the
fifth power times x to the n.

00:55:10.040 --> 00:55:12.170 align:middle line:90%
That's that ratio.

00:55:12.170 --> 00:55:15.290 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course, you
can write this in here

00:55:15.290 --> 00:55:24.440 align:middle line:84%
as just n plus 1 multiplied
by itself 5 times divided by n

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:27.290 align:middle line:90%
multiplied by itself 5 times.

00:55:27.290 --> 00:55:29.780 align:middle line:84%
And then this thing
here, you can write it

00:55:29.780 --> 00:55:36.920 align:middle line:84%
as x to the n times
x over x to the n.

00:55:36.920 --> 00:55:41.120 align:middle line:84%
So you see, this thing here,
you can then think about as n

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:53.484 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 over n to the
fifth power and times x.

00:55:53.484 --> 00:55:58.110 align:middle line:84%
And I can write this in
here in the usual way.

00:55:58.110 --> 00:56:02.670 align:middle line:84%
If you want, you can
write it as 1 plus 1/n.

00:56:02.670 --> 00:56:04.880 align:middle line:84%
I'm dividing by n
in both denominator.

00:56:04.880 --> 00:56:07.240 align:middle line:84%
And denominator, you
can write it like this,

00:56:07.240 --> 00:56:11.950 align:middle line:90%
to the fifth power times x.

00:56:11.950 --> 00:56:19.480 align:middle line:84%
And so now the root test,
it's asking whether--

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:22.390 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value
of this root test

00:56:22.390 --> 00:56:28.570 align:middle line:84%
would be then asking if
the limit here of xn plus 1

00:56:28.570 --> 00:56:34.420 align:middle line:84%
over-- oh, sorry a n plus 1 over
a n, if this here has a limit.

00:56:34.420 --> 00:56:37.010 align:middle line:90%
And then it's asking you--

00:56:37.010 --> 00:56:40.480 align:middle line:84%
if that limit is less than 1,
if it has a limit and the limit

00:56:40.480 --> 00:56:42.580 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1, then the
series is convergent.

00:56:42.580 --> 00:56:45.100 align:middle line:84%
And it's divergent if
it's bigger than 1.

00:56:45.100 --> 00:56:49.390 align:middle line:84%
But in this case, this
thing here, this ratio

00:56:49.390 --> 00:56:57.910 align:middle line:84%
here is 1 plus 1 over n to
the fifth power times x.

00:56:57.910 --> 00:56:59.450 align:middle line:90%
This is a non-negative.

00:56:59.450 --> 00:57:01.590 align:middle line:84%
So the absolute value
is just going over here.

00:57:01.590 --> 00:57:05.030 align:middle line:90%


00:57:05.030 --> 00:57:06.900 align:middle line:84%
The algebraic property
of the limit--

00:57:06.900 --> 00:57:10.760 align:middle line:84%
say that this one
here goes to 0.

00:57:10.760 --> 00:57:13.860 align:middle line:84%
And so raised to the fifth
power still goes to 0.

00:57:13.860 --> 00:57:16.490 align:middle line:84%
It's multiplying a
bunch of sequences

00:57:16.490 --> 00:57:19.880 align:middle line:84%
5 times together that
goes to 0-- to 1.

00:57:19.880 --> 00:57:22.610 align:middle line:84%
So this here, this
here goes to 1.

00:57:22.610 --> 00:57:25.170 align:middle line:84%
And so even raised to the
fifth power, still goes to 1.

00:57:25.170 --> 00:57:28.790 align:middle line:84%
So this here goes to
absolute value of x.

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:34.550 align:middle line:84%
And so the ratio test would be
that if x here-- so the ratio

00:57:34.550 --> 00:57:42.440 align:middle line:84%
test gives you is that if this
norm here is less than 1, then

00:57:42.440 --> 00:57:45.320 align:middle line:90%
this series is convergent.

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:51.560 align:middle line:84%
If the norm here is bigger
than 1, the ratio is divergent.

00:57:51.560 --> 00:57:55.110 align:middle line:84%
And it's unclear if
the norm is equal to 1.

00:57:55.110 --> 00:57:58.460 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, you see
that the ratio test here

00:57:58.460 --> 00:58:04.620 align:middle line:84%
gives you directly that the
radius of convergence is 1.

00:58:04.620 --> 00:58:10.160 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, you could
apply the root test.

00:58:10.160 --> 00:58:12.500 align:middle line:84%
The root test is
great on this here.

00:58:12.500 --> 00:58:15.487 align:middle line:90%
It's a little bit more--

00:58:15.487 --> 00:58:17.570 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you have to do a
little bit more argument.

00:58:17.570 --> 00:58:18.362 align:middle line:90%
It's not very hard.

00:58:18.362 --> 00:58:21.460 align:middle line:84%
But actually, in this
case, the ratio test

00:58:21.460 --> 00:58:27.520 align:middle line:84%
would be less to argue
than in the root test.

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:31.270 align:middle line:84%
Let's do one more
example of this.

00:58:31.270 --> 00:58:34.270 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I'll just
switch a little bit,

00:58:34.270 --> 00:58:39.070 align:middle line:84%
and then I'll come back
and review some more stuff.

00:58:39.070 --> 00:58:41.350 align:middle line:84%
I'll just talk about
a few of the problems

00:58:41.350 --> 00:58:45.080 align:middle line:84%
that I added to the
end of my review notes.

00:58:45.080 --> 00:58:48.970 align:middle line:84%
Again, I'll post this
with these problems.

00:58:48.970 --> 00:58:51.940 align:middle line:90%
And obviously, they are--

00:58:51.940 --> 00:58:54.800 align:middle line:84%
it's not exactly the
problem from the lecture.

00:58:54.800 --> 00:58:57.106 align:middle line:90%
But it's certainly [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:57.106 --> 00:59:05.473 align:middle line:90%


00:59:05.473 --> 00:59:05.973 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:05.973 --> 00:59:07.830 align:middle line:84%
And also, another
thing I want to say

00:59:07.830 --> 00:59:15.870 align:middle line:84%
is that the homework is
graded up to and including 4.

00:59:15.870 --> 00:59:18.520 align:middle line:84%
So I wasn't actually aware
of, over the weekend,

00:59:18.520 --> 00:59:20.550 align:middle line:84%
it was supposed to be
handed back within,

00:59:20.550 --> 00:59:23.740 align:middle line:84%
latest, a week of
when you handed it in.

00:59:23.740 --> 00:59:28.980 align:middle line:84%
And I just discovered it over
the weekend, that some of them

00:59:28.980 --> 00:59:30.030 align:middle line:90%
were late.

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:33.360 align:middle line:90%
But it's fixed.

00:59:33.360 --> 00:59:35.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm not the grader.

00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:40.560 align:middle line:84%
But there's two UAs that
are grading and a grader.

00:59:40.560 --> 00:59:42.070 align:middle line:90%
But it's all fixed now.

00:59:42.070 --> 00:59:48.240 align:middle line:84%
So the first four, you
can review those also

00:59:48.240 --> 00:59:55.950 align:middle line:84%
for the [? lecture. ?]
So the other power series

00:59:55.950 --> 00:59:58.390 align:middle line:90%
I want to look at is--

00:59:58.390 --> 01:00:01.846 align:middle line:84%
so again, what is the
radius of convergence?

01:00:01.846 --> 01:00:09.370 align:middle line:90%


01:00:09.370 --> 01:00:11.140 align:middle line:84%
The nice thing
about power series

01:00:11.140 --> 01:00:16.150 align:middle line:84%
is that power series is
also a test about series.

01:00:16.150 --> 01:00:18.430 align:middle line:90%
So it's like [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:18.430 --> 01:00:21.190 align:middle line:90%


01:00:21.190 --> 01:00:23.990 align:middle line:84%
And so what is the
radius of convergence?

01:00:23.990 --> 01:00:28.900 align:middle line:90%


01:00:28.900 --> 01:00:32.560 align:middle line:84%
And now the series is a
slightly different series.

01:00:32.560 --> 01:00:42.335 align:middle line:84%
It's this series
here, so this series.

01:00:42.335 --> 01:00:42.835 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:42.835 --> 01:00:45.550 align:middle line:90%
And so now let me again--

01:00:45.550 --> 01:00:48.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you could
apply the root test.

01:00:48.070 --> 01:00:54.290 align:middle line:84%
The root test is the one that
it always give you an answer.

01:00:54.290 --> 01:01:01.550 align:middle line:84%
But you may have to work
harder to find the n-th root.

01:01:01.550 --> 01:01:04.630 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes it's just
easier to use the ratio test.

01:01:04.630 --> 01:01:07.120 align:middle line:84%
So let's use the
ratio test again.

01:01:07.120 --> 01:01:10.860 align:middle line:84%
So a n here is n to
the fifth power x

01:01:10.860 --> 01:01:13.740 align:middle line:90%
to the n over n factorial.

01:01:13.740 --> 01:01:19.860 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at
a n plus 1 over a n--

01:01:19.860 --> 01:01:21.160 align:middle line:90%
maybe let me write over here.

01:01:21.160 --> 01:01:27.000 align:middle line:90%


01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:32.690 align:middle line:84%
So if I'm looking at
a n plus 1 over a n--

01:01:32.690 --> 01:01:36.780 align:middle line:90%


01:01:36.780 --> 01:01:43.680 align:middle line:84%
so then I have the n
plus 1 to the fifth power

01:01:43.680 --> 01:01:55.680 align:middle line:84%
times x to the power of n plus
1 over n plus 1 factorial.

01:01:55.680 --> 01:01:57.530 align:middle line:90%
That's a n plus 1.

01:01:57.530 --> 01:02:00.000 align:middle line:84%
And then I have
to divide by this.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:02.210 align:middle line:84%
But when I divide
by a fraction, it's

01:02:02.210 --> 01:02:09.380 align:middle line:84%
like multiplying by the inverse
of this, so like this here--

01:02:09.380 --> 01:02:17.510 align:middle line:84%
n to the n power x
to the n, like that.

01:02:17.510 --> 01:02:27.050 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, I can
write this in here as--

01:02:27.050 --> 01:02:30.240 align:middle line:84%
so if I just do
like I did before,

01:02:30.240 --> 01:02:36.240 align:middle line:84%
I would have that n plus 1
over n to the fifth power.

01:02:36.240 --> 01:02:40.640 align:middle line:84%
That's when I take this one
here and that one together.

01:02:40.640 --> 01:02:45.560 align:middle line:84%
Then when I take those two
together, I can get rid of the n

01:02:45.560 --> 01:02:46.070 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:02:46.070 --> 01:02:49.010 align:middle line:90%
And I just get an x.

01:02:49.010 --> 01:02:53.640 align:middle line:84%
And then when I look at
the ratio of these two,

01:02:53.640 --> 01:02:58.140 align:middle line:84%
this one here, n
plus 1 factorial,

01:02:58.140 --> 01:03:01.050 align:middle line:84%
you can think about
that as n plus 1

01:03:01.050 --> 01:03:03.300 align:middle line:90%
and then times n factorial.

01:03:03.300 --> 01:03:08.020 align:middle line:84%
And so this n factorial
cancel out with that,

01:03:08.020 --> 01:03:10.560 align:middle line:84%
and you're left
with an n plus 1.

01:03:10.560 --> 01:03:14.250 align:middle line:90%
So this is what you get.

01:03:14.250 --> 01:03:18.520 align:middle line:84%
And this one here, just
writing it as we did before,

01:03:18.520 --> 01:03:25.080 align:middle line:84%
dividing this fraction by
1/n in both the nominator

01:03:25.080 --> 01:03:28.230 align:middle line:84%
and denominator and
getting this thing here--

01:03:28.230 --> 01:03:33.660 align:middle line:90%
to power 5 times x, n plus 1.

01:03:33.660 --> 01:03:36.090 align:middle line:90%
And now you see that if--

01:03:36.090 --> 01:03:38.640 align:middle line:84%
and this here, I guess
it should have been

01:03:38.640 --> 01:03:40.260 align:middle line:90%
absolute value [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:40.260 --> 01:03:41.765 align:middle line:90%
So it's absolute value on this.

01:03:41.765 --> 01:03:47.610 align:middle line:90%


01:03:47.610 --> 01:03:50.990 align:middle line:90%
This one here converge to a 1.

01:03:50.990 --> 01:03:54.620 align:middle line:84%
This one is just x,
so this converge to x.

01:03:54.620 --> 01:03:57.240 align:middle line:84%
And then this here
goes to infinity.

01:03:57.240 --> 01:04:00.120 align:middle line:90%
So the ratio here goes to 0.

01:04:00.120 --> 01:04:03.380 align:middle line:84%
I'm using the algebraic
property of limits.

01:04:03.380 --> 01:04:06.500 align:middle line:90%
So this converges to 0.

01:04:06.500 --> 01:04:10.140 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
it does have a limit.

01:04:10.140 --> 01:04:12.710 align:middle line:90%
So the ratio test apply.

01:04:12.710 --> 01:04:16.340 align:middle line:84%
Because that limit
is 0 for all x,

01:04:16.340 --> 01:04:18.420 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be
converted for all x.

01:04:18.420 --> 01:04:21.070 align:middle line:84%
So the radius of
convergence in this case--

01:04:21.070 --> 01:04:29.900 align:middle line:90%


01:04:29.900 --> 01:04:33.530 align:middle line:84%
and, of course, on the
midterm, don't just

01:04:33.530 --> 01:04:36.410 align:middle line:84%
say that the radius of
convergence is infinite.

01:04:36.410 --> 01:04:38.130 align:middle line:90%
Explain this in here.

01:04:38.130 --> 01:04:40.590 align:middle line:90%
And the more detail, the better.

01:04:40.590 --> 01:04:44.750 align:middle line:84%
Because even if
there's some typos,

01:04:44.750 --> 01:04:46.100 align:middle line:90%
you should definitely get--

01:04:46.100 --> 01:04:48.040 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm not grading
the midterm either.

01:04:48.040 --> 01:04:50.410 align:middle line:84%
But you definitely should
get partial credit.

01:04:50.410 --> 01:04:51.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:04:51.300 --> 01:04:53.310 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So to get
R, is it always

01:04:53.310 --> 01:04:55.710 align:middle line:90%
like you divide by the lim sup?

01:04:55.710 --> 01:04:58.750 align:middle line:84%
Is the thing on the bottom one
the lim sup or just the lim?

01:04:58.750 --> 01:05:01.350 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

01:05:01.350 --> 01:05:07.140 align:middle line:84%
So when you take just a
complete general series,

01:05:07.140 --> 01:05:15.225 align:middle line:84%
then the radius of convergence
is, by definition, this.

01:05:15.225 --> 01:05:18.390 align:middle line:84%
This is related to-- you asked
this question a couple of times

01:05:18.390 --> 01:05:19.770 align:middle line:90%
ago that--

01:05:19.770 --> 01:05:22.540 align:middle line:84%
because we started
with the ratio test.

01:05:22.540 --> 01:05:24.390 align:middle line:84%
We did that before
we did the root test.

01:05:24.390 --> 01:05:27.300 align:middle line:84%
And you were noting
that in the ratio test,

01:05:27.300 --> 01:05:32.550 align:middle line:84%
you're always comparing an
element to the previous one.

01:05:32.550 --> 01:05:35.610 align:middle line:84%
And in general, the
series can be convergent

01:05:35.610 --> 01:05:38.100 align:middle line:84%
even though the next
element is slightly

01:05:38.100 --> 01:05:39.930 align:middle line:90%
larger than the previous.

01:05:39.930 --> 01:05:43.030 align:middle line:84%
If that keeps happening,
it's not convergent.

01:05:43.030 --> 01:05:46.800 align:middle line:84%
But it could happen a few times,
and then it goes really down.

01:05:46.800 --> 01:05:48.150 align:middle line:90%
And that's fine.

01:05:48.150 --> 01:05:56.300 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why the root test
gives you this general result

01:05:56.300 --> 01:05:59.820 align:middle line:90%
about that it always works.

01:05:59.820 --> 01:06:04.520 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't assume that a
n are not 0, et cetera.

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:08.706 align:middle line:84%
For any particular-- and it
really should be with lim sup

01:06:08.706 --> 01:06:09.320 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:06:09.320 --> 01:06:11.630 align:middle line:90%
And then it's defined.

01:06:11.630 --> 01:06:15.710 align:middle line:84%
It's a number that's
always defined.

01:06:15.710 --> 01:06:20.180 align:middle line:84%
And again, the way it's
stated here, the way the proof

01:06:20.180 --> 01:06:25.945 align:middle line:84%
goes, it's not comparing
two consecutive a n.

01:06:25.945 --> 01:06:28.610 align:middle line:90%


01:06:28.610 --> 01:06:32.240 align:middle line:84%
In any particular
example, the root test

01:06:32.240 --> 01:06:35.720 align:middle line:84%
may not be the
easiest way to argue.

01:06:35.720 --> 01:06:40.430 align:middle line:84%
Often, if you can,
for a power series,

01:06:40.430 --> 01:06:44.050 align:middle line:90%
almost always, I would say--

01:06:44.050 --> 01:06:48.970 align:middle line:84%
in a power series, it's
almost always easier

01:06:48.970 --> 01:06:50.950 align:middle line:90%
to use the ratio test.

01:06:50.950 --> 01:06:56.780 align:middle line:84%
But it requires that the power
series has some nice property

01:06:56.780 --> 01:06:58.840 align:middle line:90%
for this to apply.

01:06:58.840 --> 01:06:59.450 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:06:59.450 --> 01:07:01.180 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So the reason you
have that R as infinity

01:07:01.180 --> 01:07:02.845 align:middle line:84%
for that example
was because you know

01:07:02.845 --> 01:07:04.637 align:middle line:84%
it's convergent for
all x, not [INAUDIBLE]?

01:07:04.637 --> 01:07:07.610 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So in
this example here--

01:07:07.610 --> 01:07:08.260 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:07:08.260 --> 01:07:11.950 align:middle line:84%
This guy is infinity, which
means that this thing here

01:07:11.950 --> 01:07:13.660 align:middle line:90%
would be 0.

01:07:13.660 --> 01:07:15.190 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:07:15.190 --> 01:07:16.740 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: But you
know it's very--

01:07:16.740 --> 01:07:18.740 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: But I
didn't actually calculate.

01:07:18.740 --> 01:07:21.760 align:middle line:84%
You see, I didn't calculate the
[INAUDIBLE] in this example.

01:07:21.760 --> 01:07:24.700 align:middle line:84%
But if I had calculated
it, I would actually--

01:07:24.700 --> 01:07:26.260 align:middle line:84%
and it's not very
hard to calculate,

01:07:26.260 --> 01:07:28.130 align:middle line:90%
but it needs some small tricks.

01:07:28.130 --> 01:07:31.630 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, we haven't
talked about it.

01:07:31.630 --> 01:07:34.180 align:middle line:90%


01:07:34.180 --> 01:07:37.120 align:middle line:84%
So that's why I
didn't [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:37.120 --> 01:07:39.750 align:middle line:84%
Let me talk about
a few other things.

01:07:39.750 --> 01:07:43.440 align:middle line:90%


01:07:43.440 --> 01:07:45.140 align:middle line:84%
I didn't necessarily--
I don't think

01:07:45.140 --> 01:07:51.680 align:middle line:84%
I can probably review all
what I had in my review notes,

01:07:51.680 --> 01:07:56.900 align:middle line:84%
but let me just talk about a
few of the problems that I had.

01:07:56.900 --> 01:08:01.670 align:middle line:84%
So let me just quickly mention
the things I may or may not

01:08:01.670 --> 01:08:05.540 align:middle line:84%
get to that I have
in my review notes.

01:08:05.540 --> 01:08:12.060 align:middle line:84%
So I had also [INAUDIBLE]
what is lim sup?

01:08:12.060 --> 01:08:15.020 align:middle line:90%
What is limit final?

01:08:15.020 --> 01:08:17.335 align:middle line:90%
So definitely review that also.

01:08:17.335 --> 01:08:21.290 align:middle line:84%
We talked about the
radius of convergence.

01:08:21.290 --> 01:08:22.310 align:middle line:90%
And maybe this is all.

01:08:22.310 --> 01:08:25.819 align:middle line:84%
And then we talk a little
bit about the power series

01:08:25.819 --> 01:08:28.080 align:middle line:90%
for the exponential functions.

01:08:28.080 --> 01:08:32.750 align:middle line:84%
But again, all the stuff
we did on the power series

01:08:32.750 --> 01:08:35.540 align:middle line:90%
for the exponential functions--

01:08:35.540 --> 01:08:38.870 align:middle line:84%
and at this point, we
have established this.

01:08:38.870 --> 01:08:43.970 align:middle line:90%


01:08:43.970 --> 01:08:46.390 align:middle line:84%
There won't be anything
particular about--

01:08:46.390 --> 01:08:50.270 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the exponential function
stuff could be on the midterm.

01:08:50.270 --> 01:08:53.290 align:middle line:84%
But it's not like you
would have to prove

01:08:53.290 --> 01:08:55.880 align:middle line:84%
the properties of the
exponential function,

01:08:55.880 --> 01:08:58.765 align:middle line:84%
this property that it
has, the property that

01:08:58.765 --> 01:09:01.720 align:middle line:84%
has the exponential
function x plus y

01:09:01.720 --> 01:09:06.410 align:middle line:84%
is a part of-- that kind of
stuff, It's not on the midterm.

01:09:06.410 --> 01:09:09.069 align:middle line:90%
So it's not part of this review.

01:09:09.069 --> 01:09:11.680 align:middle line:84%
The other thing that
I probably won't

01:09:11.680 --> 01:09:13.450 align:middle line:84%
get to-- because
in a minute, I'll

01:09:13.450 --> 01:09:14.990 align:middle line:84%
just turn to these
other problems--

01:09:14.990 --> 01:09:16.750 align:middle line:90%
is that metric spaces.

01:09:16.750 --> 01:09:19.090 align:middle line:90%
Definitely review metric spaces.

01:09:19.090 --> 01:09:20.770 align:middle line:90%
It was in the last lecture.

01:09:20.770 --> 01:09:25.850 align:middle line:84%
So there's three properties
for metric space.

01:09:25.850 --> 01:09:27.590 align:middle line:84%
The distance should
be non-negative.

01:09:27.590 --> 01:09:29.020 align:middle line:90%
It should be symmetric.

01:09:29.020 --> 01:09:30.819 align:middle line:84%
And the distance
between two points

01:09:30.819 --> 01:09:33.380 align:middle line:84%
should be 0 if and only if
those points are the same.

01:09:33.380 --> 01:09:37.890 align:middle line:84%
And then the crucial
property in the metric space

01:09:37.890 --> 01:09:43.569 align:middle line:84%
that's the powerful property
is the triangle inequality.

01:09:43.569 --> 01:09:45.970 align:middle line:84%
And so there were
a few examples.

01:09:45.970 --> 01:09:48.240 align:middle line:90%
And review those examples.

01:09:48.240 --> 01:09:50.340 align:middle line:90%
They are in my review notes.

01:09:50.340 --> 01:09:53.130 align:middle line:84%
The most important
example, I would say,

01:09:53.130 --> 01:09:58.990 align:middle line:84%
is the [INAUDIBLE] metric
is kind of crazy metric.

01:09:58.990 --> 01:10:00.880 align:middle line:84%
That's not one of
the important ones.

01:10:00.880 --> 01:10:02.820 align:middle line:84%
So I just did a
review note, says

01:10:02.820 --> 01:10:04.920 align:middle line:90%
just the most important ones.

01:10:04.920 --> 01:10:06.130 align:middle line:90%
And then there's this.

01:10:06.130 --> 01:10:09.160 align:middle line:84%
What does it mean to be
convergent in a metric space?

01:10:09.160 --> 01:10:12.840 align:middle line:84%
And what does it mean
to be a Cauchy sequence?

01:10:12.840 --> 01:10:18.030 align:middle line:84%
And so now let's get to a
couple of the other problems

01:10:18.030 --> 01:10:21.630 align:middle line:84%
that I suggested
that you look at.

01:10:21.630 --> 01:10:25.565 align:middle line:84%
And so here are
two other problems.

01:10:25.565 --> 01:10:28.230 align:middle line:90%


01:10:28.230 --> 01:10:30.630 align:middle line:84%
Again, I won't get
to-- there's also

01:10:30.630 --> 01:10:32.970 align:middle line:84%
problems about metric spaces,
and you should definitely

01:10:32.970 --> 01:10:33.580 align:middle line:90%
look at it.

01:10:33.580 --> 01:10:36.430 align:middle line:84%
But I don't have the
time [INAUDIBLE],

01:10:36.430 --> 01:10:39.370 align:middle line:84%
even though it's
relevant for the midterm.

01:10:39.370 --> 01:10:40.575 align:middle line:90%
I just had to pick some.

01:10:40.575 --> 01:10:44.380 align:middle line:90%


01:10:44.380 --> 01:10:46.840 align:middle line:84%
Again, all of the
problems that I--

01:10:46.840 --> 01:10:48.500 align:middle line:90%
I have four problems here.

01:10:48.500 --> 01:10:51.250 align:middle line:90%
All of these are from midterms.

01:10:51.250 --> 01:10:56.750 align:middle line:84%
So now suppose you
take a sequence.

01:10:56.750 --> 01:10:59.390 align:middle line:90%
So I have a sequence here, xn.

01:10:59.390 --> 01:11:03.730 align:middle line:84%
And so often, a sequence
is defined recursively,

01:11:03.730 --> 01:11:18.430 align:middle line:84%
so recursively
defined sequences.

01:11:18.430 --> 01:11:20.030 align:middle line:90%
So what does it mean?

01:11:20.030 --> 01:11:23.050 align:middle line:84%
It means that,
typically, the first one

01:11:23.050 --> 01:11:25.360 align:middle line:90%
is defined to be whatever.

01:11:25.360 --> 01:11:29.560 align:middle line:84%
And then the next one is
defined from the previous one.

01:11:29.560 --> 01:11:34.170 align:middle line:84%
And so the one I was
suggesting looking at here

01:11:34.170 --> 01:11:36.710 align:middle line:84%
is that-- you said this
here, the first one.

01:11:36.710 --> 01:11:44.250 align:middle line:90%


01:11:44.250 --> 01:11:47.050 align:middle line:84%
And then actually, let me--
and then the next one--

01:11:47.050 --> 01:11:48.100 align:middle line:90%
let me just do this one.

01:11:48.100 --> 01:11:50.350 align:middle line:84%
It's actually simpler than
the one I have in my notes.

01:11:50.350 --> 01:11:53.340 align:middle line:90%
Let me do that one.

01:11:53.340 --> 01:11:57.880 align:middle line:84%
So the next one is
defined to be xn over n.

01:11:57.880 --> 01:12:05.980 align:middle line:90%


01:12:05.980 --> 01:12:14.550 align:middle line:84%
So now the question
would be, for what

01:12:14.550 --> 01:12:30.270 align:middle line:84%
a does this have a limit,
the sequence have a limit?

01:12:30.270 --> 01:12:32.388 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that in this case--

01:12:32.388 --> 01:12:33.680 align:middle line:90%
we only have four minutes left.

01:12:33.680 --> 01:12:35.000 align:middle line:90%
So I will save that for you.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:40.780 align:middle line:84%
But I just wanted you to review
what it means for a sequence

01:12:40.780 --> 01:12:44.300 align:middle line:90%
to be defined recursively, OK?

01:12:44.300 --> 01:12:46.880 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that in this case,

01:12:46.880 --> 01:12:52.280 align:middle line:84%
you have that this thing
here, it is going down.

01:12:52.280 --> 01:12:53.860 align:middle line:90%
It's actually going down.

01:12:53.860 --> 01:12:56.990 align:middle line:84%
It even could go
down by a fraction.

01:12:56.990 --> 01:12:59.440 align:middle line:84%
But now it's like, if
you're looking at this thing

01:12:59.440 --> 01:13:02.210 align:middle line:90%
here, if you're looking at xn.

01:13:02.210 --> 01:13:05.110 align:middle line:84%
This here is definitely
going to converge,

01:13:05.110 --> 01:13:07.810 align:middle line:90%
whatever you start with.

01:13:07.810 --> 01:13:16.570 align:middle line:84%
So I claim that you will always
get xn here converges to 0.

01:13:16.570 --> 01:13:22.870 align:middle line:84%
And you see that when you
have something recursively,

01:13:22.870 --> 01:13:27.320 align:middle line:84%
it often can pay to just
write out the first few terms.

01:13:27.320 --> 01:13:29.190 align:middle line:90%
So you have x and a.

01:13:29.190 --> 01:13:36.240 align:middle line:90%
x2 is equal to a.

01:13:36.240 --> 01:13:40.080 align:middle line:84%
It's also a because
it's the previous one.

01:13:40.080 --> 01:13:45.420 align:middle line:90%
x3 is now a/2.

01:13:45.420 --> 01:13:52.930 align:middle line:90%
x4 is then a/2 divided by 3.

01:13:52.930 --> 01:13:58.350 align:middle line:90%
So this is a/6 and so on.

01:13:58.350 --> 01:14:00.060 align:middle line:84%
So if you continue
like this, you

01:14:00.060 --> 01:14:02.745 align:middle line:84%
will see that they
get-- that it's like,

01:14:02.745 --> 01:14:05.910 align:middle line:84%
a divided by some larger
and larger number.

01:14:05.910 --> 01:14:11.160 align:middle line:84%
But you have to, of course,
write it nicely out as a proof.

01:14:11.160 --> 01:14:13.290 align:middle line:90%
So this is proving that.

01:14:13.290 --> 01:14:16.390 align:middle line:84%
But again, this here, if
you just did what I did,

01:14:16.390 --> 01:14:18.600 align:middle line:84%
that would not be enough
to get full credit.

01:14:18.600 --> 01:14:20.530 align:middle line:90%
So definitely write it out.

01:14:20.530 --> 01:14:24.260 align:middle line:84%
The other thing-- in the last
minutes here, the other thing--

01:14:24.260 --> 01:14:27.880 align:middle line:90%


01:14:27.880 --> 01:14:32.280 align:middle line:90%
same here [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:32.280 --> 01:14:35.190 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you take a
series like this.

01:14:35.190 --> 01:14:40.490 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that a n is
less than 1 over n squared.

01:14:40.490 --> 01:14:46.370 align:middle line:84%
And then the question could
be, is the series [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:46.370 --> 01:14:50.245 align:middle line:84%
If we knew this, but that's
all you know is the series.

01:14:50.245 --> 01:14:53.660 align:middle line:90%


01:14:53.660 --> 01:14:55.220 align:middle line:90%
Convergent or divergent?

01:14:55.220 --> 01:15:00.620 align:middle line:90%


01:15:00.620 --> 01:15:11.600 align:middle line:84%
And then I say in the
review here that either you

01:15:11.600 --> 01:15:16.490 align:middle line:84%
should prove that for all
such series it's convergent

01:15:16.490 --> 01:15:18.320 align:middle line:84%
or, if that's not
the case, you should

01:15:18.320 --> 01:15:22.610 align:middle line:84%
give an example of a series with
this property that is divergent.

01:15:22.610 --> 01:15:28.560 align:middle line:84%
Because obviously, if all the a
n was 0, it would be convergent.

01:15:28.560 --> 01:15:33.150 align:middle line:84%
But it still could be
another series with a n.

01:15:33.150 --> 01:15:35.280 align:middle line:84%
That property,
that was divergent.

01:15:35.280 --> 01:15:40.120 align:middle line:84%
But in this case, it is
going to be convergent.

01:15:40.120 --> 01:15:41.800 align:middle line:90%
And why is it convergent?

01:15:41.800 --> 01:15:45.910 align:middle line:84%
Because this series
here is convergent.

01:15:45.910 --> 01:15:47.170 align:middle line:90%
We've already seen it.

01:15:47.170 --> 01:15:50.190 align:middle line:84%
So this would be like the
simple comparison test,

01:15:50.190 --> 01:15:52.630 align:middle line:90%
like the first comparison test.

01:15:52.630 --> 01:15:58.740 align:middle line:90%


01:15:58.740 --> 01:16:03.060 align:middle line:84%
So these are just examples of
things you should be reviewing.

01:16:03.060 --> 01:16:06.150 align:middle line:90%


01:16:06.150 --> 01:16:09.840 align:middle line:84%
These things here, the
two things to the end--

01:16:09.840 --> 01:16:12.990 align:middle line:84%
this one here--
this is super fast.

01:16:12.990 --> 01:16:16.420 align:middle line:84%
So don't expect it to be
quite as fast on the midterm.

01:16:16.420 --> 01:16:21.340 align:middle line:84%
But it just gives you an idea
of what you should be doing.

01:16:21.340 --> 01:16:22.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:22.890 --> 01:16:25.000 align:middle line:90%